Now that we made our "ZONES" lets make it so that they actually mean something instead of updating every second like RSCDV25 did... Which was really shitty and in efficient.

So lets look @ that code.

[code]
	public void updateViewedPlayers() {
		List<Player> playersInView = viewArea.getPlayersInView();
		for (Player p : playersInView) {
			if (p.getIndex() != getIndex() && p.loggedIn()) {
				this.informOfPlayer(p);
				p.informOfPlayer(this);
			}
		}
[/code]

This did what reines first implemented just looked all around for every player and didnt look for them as needed to see if they needed to be updated.

If you dont believe me add this code...

[code]

	public void updateViewedPlayers() {
		List<Player> playersInView = viewArea.getPlayersInView();
		for (Player p : playersInView) {
			if (p.getIndex() != getIndex() && p.loggedIn()) {
				this.informOfPlayer(p);
				p.informOfPlayer(this);
                           System.out.println(p.getUsername() + " is being updated");
			}
		}

[/code]

It will update about every second. Why waste memory for no reason lets update them every time they walk.

[code]
	public void updateViewedPlayers() {
//Sector A
		List<Player> playersInViewA = viewArea.getPlayersSectorA();
		for (Player p : playersInViewA) {
			if (p.getIndex() != getIndex() && p.loggedIn() && System.currentTimeMillis() - p.getLastMoved() < 1000) {
System.out.println(p.getUsername() + " walked inside + " this.getUsername() + "'s sector A");
				this.informOfPlayer(p);
				p.informOfPlayer(this);
			}
		}
//Sector B
		List<Player> playersInViewB = viewArea.getPlayersSectorB();
